SIMPLE: warish
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warish
<hw>War"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>warir</ets> to protect, heal, cure, F. <ets>gu⟦eacute⟧ri<?/</ets>
to cure; of Teutonic origin; cf. OHG. <ets>werian</ets>,
<ets>weren</ets>, to protect, to hinder. See <er>Garret</er>.]</ety>
<def>To protect from the effects of; hence, to cure; to heal.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My brother shall be <qex>warished</qex> hastily.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Varro testifies that even at this day there be some who
<qex>warish</qex> and cure the stinging of serpents with their
spittle.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Warish
<hw>War"ish</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be cured; to recover.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your daughter . . . shall <qex>warish</qex> and escape.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warison</ent>⟦br⟧
